======================================================================
PART 3: THE SIMPLEX-CUBOID PACKING RATIO AT EACH n
======================================================================

  The ratio (x+2)^n / (x+1)^n = ((x+2)/(x+1))^n
  At x=1: (3/2)^n — grows exponentially

  n= 1: (3/2)^n =      1.500, n! =        1, 2^n =     2, corners =        0
  n= 2: (3/2)^n =      2.250, n! =        2, 2^n =     4, corners = N/A (no Hadamard)
  n= 3: (3/2)^n =      3.375, n! =        6, 2^n =     8, corners =        4
  n= 4: (3/2)^n =      5.062, n! =       24, 2^n =    16, corners = N/A (no Hadamard)
  n= 5: (3/2)^n =      7.594, n! =      120, 2^n =    32, corners = N/A (no Hadamard)
  n= 6: (3/2)^n =     11.391, n! =      720, 2^n =    64, corners = N/A (no Hadamard)
  n= 7: (3/2)^n =     17.086, n! =     5040, 2^n =   128, corners =      120
  n= 8: (3/2)^n =     25.629, n! =    40320, 2^n =   256, corners = N/A (no Hadamard)
  n= 9: (3/2)^n =     38.443, n! =   362880, 2^n =   512, corners = N/A (no Hadamard)
  n=10: (3/2)^n =     57.665, n! =  3628800, 2^n =  1024, corners = N/A (no Hadamard)
  n=11: (3/2)^n =     86.498, n! = 39916800, 2^n =  2048, corners =     2036
  n=12: (3/2)^n =    129.746, n! = 479001600, 2^n =  4096, corners = N/A (no Hadamard)

  Volume ratios for Hadamard simplices:
  (Regular simplex inscribed in unit cube)

  n=1: cube/simplex = 1, corners = 0, each corner/simplex = 0.0000, 
  n=2: cube/simplex = 2, corners = 1, each corner/simplex = 1.0000, 
  n=3: cube/simplex = 3, corners = 4, each corner/simplex = 0.5000, = 1/2 ✓
  n=7: cube/simplex = 157.5, corners = 120, each corner/simplex = 1.3042, 

  The 'halves' property (each corner = simplex/2) holds ONLY at n=2,3!
  At n=7: each corner = 1.29× the simplex — they're LARGER than the simplex.

======================================================================
PART 4: THE (x+1)/(x+2) FRAMEWORK FOR TOURNAMENTS
======================================================================

  Computing I(Ω, x) for all n=5 tournaments:

    α₁  H=I(2)  I(3) I(-1) I(3)/I(2)  count
     0       1     1     1    1.0000    120
     1       3     4     0    1.3333    120
     2       5     7    -1    1.4000    240
     4       9    13    -3    1.4444    240
     5      11    16    -4    1.4545    120
     6      13    19    -5    1.4615    120
     7      15    22    -6    1.4667     64

  SIMPLEX-CUBOID DECOMPOSITION of I(Ω, x):
  I(Ω, x) = 1 + α₁x + α₂x² + ...
  In the (x+1)^k basis: simplex decomposition
  In the (x+2)^k basis: cuboid decomposition

  Basis change: x = (x+1) - 1 = (x+2) - 2
  So: I = 1 + α₁((x+1)-1) = (1-α₁) + α₁(x+1)
  At n=5 (α₂=0): I = (1-α₁) + α₁·(x+1)
  This is LINEAR in (x+1)!

  Simplex coefficients [c₀, c₁]: I = c₀ + c₁(x+1)
  c₀ = I(x=-1) = I(-1) = 1-α₁
  c₁ = α₁

  Cuboid coefficients [d₀, d₁]: I = d₀ + d₁(x+2)
  d₀ = I(x=-2) = I(-2) = 1-2α₁
  d₁ = α₁

  At x=1 (key 2): I(1) = (1-α₁) + 2α₁ = 1+α₁ (= H for 3-cycles only)
  Wait, I(2) = H. Let me recompute.
  I(x) = 1 + α₁x: I(2) = 1+2α₁ = H. ✓
  In simplex basis: I = (1-α₁) + α₁(x+1)
    At x=2: (1-α₁) + 3α₁ = 1+2α₁ = H. ✓

  H - I(-1) = Σ αₖ(2^k - (-1)^k)
  For k=1: coefficient 3 = 2+1
  For k=2: coefficient 3 = 4-1
  For k=3: coefficient 9 = 8+1
  For k=4: coefficient 15 = 16-1

  These are 2^k + (-1)^{k+1} = 3, 3, 9, 15, 33, 63, ...
  For k=1,2: both equal 3! The first two levels contribute equally.
  This is why α₁ ≥ α₂ is 'natural': levels 1 and 2 have equal weight in H-I(-1).

